<ab><lb n="0"/><gap id="iaph2005-gap01" reason="lost" unit="line" extent="unknown"/><certainty degree="low" locus="#gi" target="iaph2005-gap01"/><lb n="1"/><w lemma="τιμάω"><orig reg="ἐτίμησεν"><supplied reason="lost">ἐ</supplied><unclear reason="damage">τ</unclear><supplied reason="lost">είμησεν</supplied></orig></w><lb n="2"/><persName nymRef="#Χαιρέας" type="attested"><name nymRef="#Χαιρέας"><supplied reason="lost">Χ</supplied>αιρέαν</name></persName>  <lb n="3"/><w lemma="ὁ">τὸν</w> <w lemma="στεφανηφόρος">στε<lb n="4" break="no"/>φανηφό<lb n="5" break="no"/>ρον</w>.</ab></div>
         <div type="apparatus">
            <p>Cormack saw the trace of an upright in l. 1, and so read <foreign xml:lang="grc">
                  <supplied reason="lost">ἐ</supplied>τ<supplied reason="lost">είμησεν</supplied>
               </foreign>; but this might be a trace left by the moulding.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>
               <gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/>
               <supplied reason="lost" cert="low">honoured</supplied> Chaireas the stephanephoros.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>There may have been a verb of honouring on an upper feature; but the two texts, <ref type="inscription" n="1004" target="120602.xml"/> and <ref type="inscription" n="1005" target="110409.xml"/> (= MAMA 466, 467), both very similar, may perhaps be complete.</p>
         </div>
